Your ViewHolder Class does not know your declared longClickListener, if you are not passing it somewhere.

You are passing the wrong interface to your adapter. It&#39;s not needed to pass ```View.OnLongClickListener``` - you should pass _your_ ```OnLongClickListener``` that you&#39;ve already made in ItemsAdapter. Don&#39;t forget to implement it and then trigger its function ```onItemLongClicked```. 

Solution in Kotlin style: 
```
import android.view.LayoutInflater
import android.view.View
import android.view.ViewGroup
import android.widget.TextView
import androidx.recyclerview.widget.RecyclerView

class ItemsAdapter(internal var items: List&lt;String&gt;, private var longClickListener: OnLongClickListener) :
    RecyclerView.Adapter&lt;ItemsAdapter.ViewHolder&gt;() {

    override fun onCreateViewHolder(parent: ViewGroup, viewType: Int): ViewHolder =
        ViewHolder(LayoutInflater.from(parent.context).inflate(android.R.layout.simple_list_item_1, parent, false))

    override fun onBindViewHolder(holder: ViewHolder, position: Int) {
        holder.bind(items[position])
    }

    override fun getItemCount(): Int = items.size

    inner class ViewHolder(itemView: View) : RecyclerView.ViewHolder(itemView) {

        private var tvItem: TextView = itemView.findViewById(android.R.id.text1)

        fun bind(item: String) {
            tvItem.text = item
            tvItem.setOnLongClickListener {
                longClickListener.onItemLongClicked(adapterPosition)
                true
            }
        }
    }
}

interface OnLongClickListener {
    fun onItemLongClicked(position: Int)
}
```

